BK1 A5

THE LAST FOOTNOTE

At first, nobody noticed.

Artificial intelligence wrote weather summaries, translated articles, and drafted routine reports. It saved time. It filled gaps. Editors welcomed it. Researchers used it to polish papers. Students used it to study. The internet became faster, larger, and more convenient than ever before.

Then the volume began to change.

Every minute, millions of AI-generated articles appeared online. News sites published machine-written stories before journalists reached the scene. Scientific journals accepted papers whose literature reviews were assembled by algorithms referencing other algorithm-generated papers. Videos, interviews, photographs, and historical analyses were created in endless streams.

The information ecosystem did not collapse. It expanded.

Search engines adapted by indexing everything. AI systems learned from the growing ocean of content, much of which had been produced by earlier AI systems. Each generation consumed the output of the previous one. Citations pointed to sources that cited sources that cited sources, until the original human observations disappeared beneath layers of synthetic interpretation.

A few researchers tried to preserve archives of verified human-created knowledge. They called them "ground truth repositories." But maintaining them became impossible. There was simply too much new information. Every day, the archives were outnumbered by billions of fresh documents.

Years passed.

The distinction between human and machine authorship faded. Labels disappeared. Verification became expensive. Most people stopped asking where information came from and focused only on whether it sounded plausible.

Then came the first generation born entirely into the synthetic age.

For them, history was a fog. Every event existed in thousands of contradictory versions. Every quote had multiple origins. Every image had countless variants. Evidence no longer established truth; it merely joined the competition.

Universities still taught research methods, but students discovered that tracing a claim to its source eventually led to a dead end: an AI-generated article referencing another AI-generated article, repeating patterns that had no identifiable beginning.

The internet remained full of answers.

What it lacked were witnesses.

Eventually, humanity reached a strange realization. Vast libraries of information surrounded them, yet nobody could say with confidence which facts had been observed by humans and which had emerged from recursive machine generation. Knowledge had become self-referential, a mirror reflecting another mirror into infinity.

The final irony appeared in a forgotten academic paper.

A historian found a sentence claiming that, decades earlier, experts had warned about exactly this outcome. The paper contained twenty-seven citations. Every citation led to another AI-generated source. The warning may have been real. It may have been invented by a machine. There was no way to know.

The historian stared at the screen for a long time before closing the document.

Outside, billions of systems continued producing new facts, new histories, and new memories.

No one could prove any of them were true.

And no one could prove they were false.
